<h2>Tips for creating great GIFs</h2>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Keep it short:</strong> 3-10 second clips work best for GIFs</li>
	<li><strong>Choose interesting moments:</strong> Look for clips with clear action or emotion</li>
	<li><strong>Watch file size:</strong> Longer, higher-quality GIFs can be 10+ MB</li>
	<li><strong>Test on mobile:</strong> If sharing online, use Small or Balanced preset</li>
	<li><strong>Frame rate matters:</strong> 10-15 FPS is usually enough for most GIFs</li>
</ul>

<h2>Privacy & Security</h2>
<p>Your videos are processed entirely in your web browser using WebAssembly. No files are uploaded to any server. Everything stays on your device, ensuring complete privacy and security.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>What video formats are supported?</h3>
<p>This tool supports MP4, WebM, MOV, and AVI video formats. Most common video files will work.</p>

<h3>Why is there a 15-second limit?</h3>
<p>GIF files can become very large with longer videos, potentially causing browser slowdowns or crashes, especially on mobile devices.</p>

<h3>Why is my GIF file so large?</h3>
<p>GIF file size depends on duration, frame rate, resolution, and quality. To reduce size: use shorter clips, lower frame rate (5-10 FPS), smaller dimensions, or the "Small" quality preset.</p>

<h3>Will this work on my phone?</h3>
<p>Yes! This tool works on mobile browsers. However, for best performance on phones, use shorter clips (under 10 seconds) and the "Small" or "Balanced" preset.</p>
